{
  "text": "We have generated a considerable amount of data that suggests selective FA metabolism is a major determinant of tissue FA profile in sunshine bass [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ); however, incorporation or exclusion of FAs varies among lipid classes [CITATION_3] ). The paradigm of selective FA metabolism invokes selective incorporation of certain FAs during new tissue synthesis or lipid accumulation, via remodeling of existing lipid fractions, or some combination thereof. Growth can occur via hyperplastic (increases in total number of cells) or hypertrophic (increases in individual cell size) processes. In fishes, muscular hypertrophy is associated with rapid weight gain, whereas muscular hyperplasia is associated with slower growth [CITATION_4] ). Although both processes are occurring to some extent, juvenile growth in fishes is generally dominated by hypertrophic growth [CITATION_5] . By their nature, muscular hypertrophy and hyperplasia are associated with greater synthesis and accumulation of neutral (i.e., triacylglyceride [TAG] ) and polar (i.e., phospholipid [PL]) lipids, respectively. Given the differences in FA selectivity and plasticity within these lipid classes (Trushenski et al., in press) , one might expect a FA profile change during rapid (hypertrophic) 5.5 6 0.6 x 6.6 6 0.6 yx 9.5 6 0.6 z 7.5 6 0.6 y 9.8 6 0.6 z ,0.001 Total SFA a 23.2 6 0.8 w 31.3 6 0.8 y 45.0 6 0.9 z 28.0 6 0.8 x 31.0 6 0.8 y ,0.001",
